\noindent \textbf{Q6. [Physics - Work, Power, Energy \& Calculus]} \\
A flexible chain of mass $M$ and length $L=10$ m is held on a smooth horizontal table such that a tiny fraction hangs through a hole. It is released from rest. The linear mass density varies as $\lambda(x) = kx$, where $x$ is the distance from the end at the hole. Find the velocity squared ($v^2$ in m$^2$/s$^2$) of the chain when it completely slips through the hole. (Take $g = 10 \text{ m/s}^2$).

\newpage
\begin{center}
    \Large\textbf{SOLUTIONS \& EXPLANATIONS}
\end{center}
\vspace{0.5cm}

\textbf{Q1. Answer: (A), (B), (D)} \\
\textit{Concept:} Constrained Motion. Because the string is tied to the wall, if the wedge moves right by $x$, the pulley moves right by $x$. The horizontal string segment releases $x$ length. To keep the string taut, the block must slide DOWN the incline by $x$. Hence, $a_{rel} = a_w$. \\
Using Newton's Laws in wedge frame: $N = m(g\cos\theta + a\sin\theta)$. 
Equation along incline: $mg\sin\theta - ma\cos\theta - T = m(a)$. \\
FBD of Wedge: Horizontal forces are $T$ (from wall pulling right), $-T\cos\theta$ (from block), and $-N\sin\theta$. 
Solving $T(1-\cos\theta) - N\sin\theta = Ma$ gives $a = \frac{mg \sin \theta (1 - 2\cos \theta)}{M + 2m \sin^2 \theta}$. \\
If $\theta < 60^\circ$, $1 - 2\cos\theta < 0$, so $a_w < 0$ (moves left).

\vspace{0.5cm}
\textbf{Q2. Answer: (A), (B), (C)} \\
\textit{Concept:} Mechanical equilibrium to Thermodynamics. $P_{gas} A = k x$. Since $V = Ax$, $P = \frac{k}{A^2} V \implies P \propto V$. This is a polytropic process $PV^{-1} = const$ ($n = -1$). 
$C = C_v + \frac{R}{1-n} = 1.5R + 0.5R = 2R$. \\
Heat fraction $\Delta U / \Delta Q = 1.5R / 2R = 0.75$ (75\%). \\
Work done $W = \int P dV$. Area under P-V graph is a triangle, $W = \frac{1}{2} nR\Delta T = 0.5 R T_0$. Option D is false.

\vspace{0.5cm}
\textbf{Q3. Answer: (A), (C)} \\
\textit{Concept:} Telescoping sequence. $x_{n+1} = x_n^2 - x_n - 1 \implies x_{n+1} - x_n = x_n^2 - 2x_n - 1$. 
Rewrite as $x_{n+1} + 1 = x_n(x_n - 1)$. Taking reciprocals: $\frac{1}{x_n - 1} - \frac{1}{x_n} = \frac{1}{x_{n+1} + 1}$. 
The identity is $\frac{1}{x_n+1} = \frac{1}{x_n} - \frac{1}{x_{n+1}}$. The sum $\sum \frac{1}{x_n}$ evaluates perfectly to $\frac{1}{x_1 - 1} = \frac{1}{3-1} = \frac{1}{2}$.

\vspace{0.5cm}
\textbf{Q4. Answer: 141.21} \\
\textit{Concept:} Stoichiometry + Heat. $NH_3$ (4 mol) limits the reaction. 4 moles of solid formed. 2 moles of $HCl$ gas remain.
Heat released $q = 4 \times 42,000 = 168,000$ J. 
Gas heats up: $q = n C_v \Delta T \implies 168,000 = 2 \times 21 \times \Delta T \implies \Delta T = 4000$ K.
$T_{final} = 300 + 4000 = 4300$ K.
$P_{final} = \frac{n R T_{final}}{V} = \frac{2 \times 0.0821 \times 4300}{5} = 141.21$ atm.

\vspace{0.5cm}
\textbf{Q5. Answer: 48} \\
\textit{Concept:} Roots and Geometry. $PA + PB = 12$, $PA \cdot PB = 24$.
Chord $AB = PB - PA = \sqrt{(PA+PB)^2 - 4(PA \cdot PB)} = \sqrt{144 - 96} = \sqrt{48}$.
Since $AB$ subtends $60^\circ$ at the center, $\Delta OAB$ is equilateral. Radius $R = AB = \sqrt{48}$.
Area $= \pi R^2 = 48\pi$. $K = 48$.

\vspace{0.5cm}
\textbf{Q6. Answer: 133.33} \\
\textit{Concept:} Variable Mass WPE. Total mass $M = \int_0^L kx dx = kL^2/2$.
Loss in PE of the whole chain when it drops vertically $= \int_0^L (dm) g y$. $dm = ky dy$.
$\Delta PE = \int_0^L kyg y dy = k g [y^3/3] = kgL^3/3$.
Gain in KE $= \frac{1}{2} M v^2 = \frac{1}{2} (kL^2/2) v^2 = \frac{kL^2}{4} v^2$.
Equating: $v^2 = \frac{4gL}{3} = \frac{4 \times 10 \times 10}{3} = 133.33$.

